│   Value *LHS = (NarrowUse->getOperand(0) == NarrowDef)                        │
│                    ? WideDef                                                  │
│                    : createExtendInst(NarrowUse->getOperand(0), WideType,     │
│                                       SignExtend, NarrowUse);                 │
│                                                                               │
│   Value *RHS;                                                                 │
│   if (NarrowUse->getOperand(1) == NarrowDef) {                                │
│     if (BothIV && SignExtend) {                                               │
│       // To match the SCEV-selected recurrence, extend one IV operand         │
│ explicitly.                                                                   │
│       RHS = createExtendInst(NarrowDef, WideType, SignExtend, NarrowUse);     │
│     } else {                                                                  │
│       RHS = WideDef;                                                          │
│     }                                                                         │
│   } else {                                                                    │
│     RHS = createExtendInst(NarrowUse->getOperand(1), WideType,                │
│                            SignExtend, NarrowUse);                            │
│   }                                                                           │
│                                                                               │
│ This ensures that when both operands are the IV and sign extension is         │
│ required to match the chosen AddRec, we actually materialize zext(iv) +       │
│ sext(iv), preserving semantics. For the cases where the operand is not the    │
│ IV, or when zero extension suffices (e.g., non-negative ranges), behavior     │
│ remains unchanged.                                                            │
│                                                                               │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                                │
│ The bug is in IV widening, not LCSSA. WidenIV::cloneArithmeticIVUser fails to │
│ honor the chosen extension kind when both operands are the same narrow IV,    │
│ leading to incorrect transformation of zext(add i16 iv, iv) into add i32      │
│ zext(iv), zext(iv). By explicitly extending one of the operands in the        │
│ both-operands-are-IV case, we align the widened IR with the AddRec that SCEV  │
│ deemed equivalent to the correctly extended narrow expression, fixing the     │
│ miscompile and restoring the correct return value (65512) for the reproducer. │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                               │
