  "reason_thou": "1. Understanding the Issue:\nThe miscompile arises from
IndVarSimplify's IV widening logic when a binary op in the loop uses the same
induction variable on both operands, and a zero/sign extension of the result is
used outside the loop. In the reproducer, the loop computes add i16 %indvar,
%indvar followed by zext to i32. IndVarSimplify widens %indvar to i32 and then
tries to eliminate the zext by cloning the i16 add as an i32 add of widened
values. However, when both operands are the same IV and the only correct widening
requires sign-extending one operand (to match SCEV semantics), the current code
incorrectly replaces both operands by the widened IV, effectively computing
zext(%indvar) + zext(%indvar) instead of the required zext(%indvar) +
sext(%indvar). For negative initial values this changes semantics (e.g., -12
case: 65512 vs 131048).\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\n- SCEV prints %ext as the
addrec {65512,+,2}<nuw><nsw>, which matches the semantics of zext(i16(2*iv)).\n-
LCSSA is the first pass to make a structural change (inserting LCSSA PHIs). It is
not transforming semantics; it is just exposing the PHI that IndVarSimplify will
later target.\n- The target IR shows ret i32 131048 = 2 * zext(-12) instead of
zext(i16(-12 + -12)) = 65512, revealing that a widening step replaced zext(add
i16 iv, iv) by add i32 zext(iv), zext(iv).\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nIn
WidenIV::cloneArithmeticIVUser (SimplifyIndVar.cpp), when widening a narrow
binary op that uses the IV, the code tries to choose whether the non-IV operand
should be zero or sign extended so that SCEV(WideDef op Ext(NonIV)) equals the
AddRec expected for the widened expression. For the pattern add i16 iv, iv, the
correct widened expression to match {65512,+,2} is zext(iv) + sext(iv). The
helper GuessNonIVOperand correctly concludes that sign extension is needed.
However, the current cloning code contains a structural assumption: if an operand
equals the narrow IV, it uses the widened IV (WideDef) for that operand;
otherwise it inserts an extension. When both operands equal the narrow IV, both
get replaced with WideDef, and the selected sign-extend is ignored. This yields
add i32 WideDef, WideDef (i.e., zext(iv) + zext(iv)), which is wrong for negative
iv.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s)\nFile:
llvm/lib/Transforms/Utils/SimplifyIndVar.cpp\nLocation: In
WidenIV::cloneArithmeticIVUser, right after deciding SignExtend and before
building the BinaryOperator (currently lines ~1358-1374 in the provided listing).
We need to special-case when both operands equal NarrowDef and the chosen
extension for the \u201cother\u201d operand is sign (or zero, in general),
materializing an explicit extend for one of the operands instead of using WideDef
for both.\n\nEdit intent:\n- Detect \"BothIV\" = (op0 == NarrowDef && op1 ==
NarrowDef).\n- If BothIV and a specific extension kind was selected
(SignExtend==true or false as determined by GuessNonIVOperand), construct one
operand as the extension of the narrow IV using that kind, and the other as
WideDef. Prefer to extend the RHS for determinism.\n- Otherwise, keep existing
logic.\n\nPatch (conceptual):\n\nReplace the LHS/RHS selection block with:\n\n
bool BothIV = (NarrowUse->getOperand(0) == NarrowDef) &&\n
(NarrowUse->getOperand(1) == NarrowDef);\n\n  Value *LHS =
(NarrowUse->getOperand(0) == NarrowDef)\n                   ? WideDef\n
: createExtendInst(NarrowUse->getOperand(0), WideType,\n
SignExtend, NarrowUse);\n\n  Value *RHS;\n  if (NarrowUse->getOperand(1) ==
NarrowDef) {\n    if (BothIV && SignExtend) {\n      // To match the
SCEV-selected recurrence, extend one IV operand explicitly.\n      RHS =
createExtendInst(NarrowDef, WideType, SignExtend, NarrowUse);\n    } else {\n
RHS = WideDef;\n    }\n  } else {\n    RHS =
createExtendInst(NarrowUse->getOperand(1), WideType,\n
SignExtend, NarrowUse);\n  }\n\nThis ensures that when both operands are the IV
and sign extension is required to match the chosen AddRec, we actually
materialize zext(iv) + sext(iv), preserving semantics. For the cases where the
operand is not the IV, or when zero extension suffices (e.g., non-negative
ranges), behavior remains unchanged.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nThe bug is in IV
widening, not LCSSA. WidenIV::cloneArithmeticIVUser fails to honor the chosen
extension kind when both operands are the same narrow IV, leading to incorrect
transformation of zext(add i16 iv, iv) into add i32 zext(iv), zext(iv). By
explicitly extending one of the operands in the both-operands-are-IV case, we
align the widened IR with the AddRec that SCEV deemed equivalent to the correctly
extended narrow expression, fixing the miscompile and restoring the correct
return value (65512) for the reproducer.",
